  "prompt": "What is Fiverr, and how do they make money?",
  "response": "Fiverr is an online marketplace that connects freelancers with clients seeking services across various categories, including graphic design, writing, programming, marketing, video editing, and more. Founded in 2010, Fiverr allows individuals and businesses to offer their services (referred to as \"gigs\") at a starting price of $5, although services can be priced much higher depending on complexity and demand.\n\n### How Fiverr Makes Money:\n\nFiverr primarily generates revenue through the following methods:\n\n1. **Service Fees**: Fiverr charges a service fee on transactions between buyers and sellers. When a freelancer completes a project and the buyer pays for it, Fiverr takes a percentage of the total amount as a fee. Typically, this fee is around 20%, but it can vary based on the type of service and arrangements made.\n\n2. **Promoted Gigs**: Freelancers can pay for additional visibility for their gigs through a promoted listings feature. By paying to have their gigs displayed more prominently, freelancers can increase their chances of getting hired, and Fiverr earns revenue from these advertising fees.\n\n3. **Subscription Services**: Fiverr offers subscription plans, such as Fiverr Business, which caters to larger teams and organizations. These plans provide additional features like enhanced collaboration tools, access to a curated selection of freelancers, and more. Fiverr charges businesses a subscription fee for these services.\n\n4. **Fiverr Learn**: Fiverr also provides educational courses for freelancers and entrepreneurs through its Fiverr Learn platform. While some courses are free, many are paid, contributing to Fiverr's overall revenue.\n\n5. **Fiverr Pro**: This is a premium service that connects clients with top-rated freelancers who have been vetted by Fiverr. Fiverr takes a cut from these premium gigs, often at higher price points, thus increasing its revenue.\n\nThrough these revenue streams, Fiverr has established itself as a major player in the freelance marketplace, capitalizing on the growing gig economy and the demand for flexible work arrangements.",
